Identified Weakness:

The rule only detects lateral movement after multiple NTLM authentications, missing earlier high-signal credential dumping activity that precedes the attack.

Before (Existing Rule):
IdentityLogonEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(10m)
| where Protocol == "NTLM"
| summarize TargetHosts = dcount(DeviceName), HostList = make_set(DeviceName) 
    by AccountName, DeviceName, bin(TimeGenerated, 5m)
| where TargetHosts >= 3

After (Improved Rule):
// Step 1: Detect potential credential dumping (LSASS access)
let CredentialDumping = DeviceProcessEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(30m)
| where ProcessCommandLine has_any ("lsass", "comsvcs.dll", "MiniDump", "sekurlsa")  // LSASS dump indicators
| project DumpTime = TimeGenerated, DeviceName;

// Step 2: Detect NTLM authentication spread from same device
let NTLMActivity = IdentityLogonEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(30m)
| where Protocol == "NTLM"
| summarize TargetHosts = dcount(DestinationDeviceName), HostList = make_set(DestinationDeviceName)
    by AccountName, DeviceName, bin(TimeGenerated, 5m)
| where TargetHosts >= 2;  // Lower threshold for earlier signal

// Step 3: Correlate dumping with subsequent NTLM activity
CredentialDumping
| join kind=inner (NTLMActivity) on DeviceName
| where NTLMActivity_TimeGenerated > DumpTime  // Ensure sequence: dump → movement
| project DumpTime, NTLMTime = NTLMActivity_TimeGenerated, DeviceName, AccountName, TargetHosts, HostList

Explanation:
Detection accuracy: By correlating LSASS dumping with NTLM activity, the rule focuses on true attack sequences (credential access → lateral movement), reducing false positives from benign NTLM usage.
Noise reduction: Instead of alerting on every multi-host NTLM event, it requires a preceding suspicious action (credential dumping), which is rare in legitimate operations.
Earlier detection: Lowering the NTLM threshold and anchoring detection to the dump event enables alerting shortly after initial movement begins—potentially catching the attacker over an hour earlier in this case.